This article celebrates the 200th birthday of Susan B. Anthony, a prominent advocate for women's rights and suffrage. It acknowledges her role in paving the way for the ratification of the 19th Amendment, which granted women the right to vote in 1920. The article also recognizes Anthony's work in advocating for the sanctity of all human life and her efforts against slavery. It emphasizes the importance of protecting the rights of all Americans and fostering mutual respect and understanding in society. The article concludes by applauding the achievements of women who have contributed to the prosperity, safety, and success of the United States.